The agreement covers nearly a third of the world’s economic output and affects 600 million people. LONDON - One of the world’s biggest free-trade deals has been agreed between the European Union and Japan. The agreement covers nearly a third of the world’s economic output and affects 600 million people. A free-trade deal couldn’t be timelier as US President Donald Trump has introduced tough imports tariffs and threatened a trade war with the rest of the world. Japan and the EU have reached a massive free-trade agreement. Firms in Europe, the world’s biggest free-trade zone, currently export more than $100 billion in goods and services to Japan every year. However, it’s particularly significant for the motor manufacturing industry in Japan, a key exporter to the rest of the world and it secures the export of dairy goods from the European Union to Japan. (Edited by Zamangwane Shange)